391/** Base class to provide completion handler boilerplate for composed operations.
392
393 A function object submitted to intermediate initiating functions during
394 a composed operation may derive from this type to inherit all of the
395 boilerplate to forward the executor, allocator, and legacy customization
396 points associated with the completion handler invoked at the end of the
397 composed operation.
398
399 The composed operation must be typical; that is, associated with one
400 executor of an I/O object, and invoking a caller-provided completion
401 handler when the operation is finished. Classes derived from
402 @ref async_base will acquire these properties:
403
404 @li Ownership of the final completion handler provided upon construction.
405
406 @li If the final handler has an associated allocator, this allocator will
407 be propagated to the composed operation subclass. Otherwise, the
408 associated allocator will be the type specified in the allocator
409 template parameter, or the default of `std::allocator<void>` if the
410 parameter is omitted.
411
412 @li If the final handler has an associated executor, then it will be used
413 as the executor associated with the composed operation. Otherwise,
414 the specified `Executor1` will be the type of executor associated
415 with the composed operation.
416
417 @li An instance of `net::executor_work_guard` for the instance of `Executor1`
418 shall be maintained until either the final handler is invoked, or the
419 operation base is destroyed, whichever comes first.
420
421 @li Calls to the legacy customization points
422 `asio_handler_invoke`,
423 `asio_handler_allocate`,
424 `asio_handler_deallocate`, and
425 `asio_handler_is_continuation`,
426 which use argument-dependent lookup, will be forwarded to the
427 legacy customization points associated with the handler.
428
429 Data members of composed operations implemented as completion handlers
430 do not have stable addresses, as the composed operation object is move
431 constructed upon each call to an initiating function. For most operations
432 this is not a problem. For complex operations requiring stable temporary
433 storage, the class @ref stable_async_base is provided which offers
434 additional functionality:
435
436 @li The free function @ref beast::allocate_stable may be used to allocate
437 one or more temporary objects associated with the composed operation.
438
439 @li Memory for stable temporary objects is allocated using the allocator
440 associated with the composed operation.
441
442 @li Stable temporary objects are automatically destroyed, and the memory
443 freed using the associated allocator, either before the final completion
444 handler is invoked (a Networking requirement) or when the composed operation
445 is destroyed, whichever occurs first.
446
447 @par Example
448
449 The following code demonstrates how @ref stable_async_base may be be used to
450 assist authoring an asynchronous initiating function, by providing all of
451 the boilerplate to manage the final completion handler in a way that maintains
452 the allocator and executor associations. Furthermore, the operation shown
453 allocates temporary memory using @ref beast::allocate_stable for the timer and
454 message, whose addresses must not change between intermediate operations:
455
456 @code
457
458 // Asynchronously send a message multiple times, once per second
459 template <class AsyncWriteStream, class T, class WriteHandler>
460 auto async_write_messages(
461 AsyncWriteStream& stream,
462 T const& message,
463 std::size_t repeat_count,
464 WriteHandler&& handler) ->
465 typename net::async_result<
466 typename std::decay<WriteHandler>::type,
467 void(error_code)>::return_type
468 {
469 using handler_type = typename net::async_completion<WriteHandler, void(error_code)>::completion_handler_type;
470 using base_type = stable_async_base<handler_type, typename AsyncWriteStream::executor_type>;
471
472 struct op : base_type, boost::asio::coroutine
473 {
474 // This object must have a stable address
475 struct temporary_data
476 {
477 // Although std::string is in theory movable, most implementations
478 // use a "small buffer optimization" which means that we might
479 // be submitting a buffer to the write operation and then
480 // moving the string, invalidating the buffer. To prevent
481 // undefined behavior we store the string object itself at
482 // a stable location.
483 std::string const message;
484
485 net::steady_timer timer;
486
487 temporary_data(std::string message_, net::io_context& ctx)
488 : message(std::move(message_))
489 , timer(ctx)
490 {
491 }
492 };
493
494 AsyncWriteStream& stream_;
495 std::size_t repeats_;
496 temporary_data& data_;
497
498 op(AsyncWriteStream& stream, std::size_t repeats, std::string message, handler_type& handler)
499 : base_type(std::move(handler), stream.get_executor())
500 , stream_(stream)
501 , repeats_(repeats)
502 , data_(allocate_stable<temporary_data>(*this, std::move(message), stream.get_executor().context()))
503 {
504 (*this)(); // start the operation
505 }
506
507 // Including this file provides the keywords for macro-based coroutines
508 #include <boost/asio/yield.hpp>
509
510 void operator()(error_code ec = {}, std::size_t = 0)
511 {
512 reenter(*this)
513 {
514 // If repeats starts at 0 then we must complete immediately. But
515 // we can't call the final handler from inside the initiating
516 // function, so we post our intermediate handler first. We use
517 // net::async_write with an empty buffer instead of calling
518 // net::post to avoid an extra function template instantiation, to
519 // keep compile times lower and make the resulting executable smaller.
520 yield net::async_write(stream_, net::const_buffer{}, std::move(*this));
521 while(! ec && repeats_-- > 0)
522 {
523 // Send the string. We construct a `const_buffer` here to guarantee
524 // that we do not create an additional function template instantation
525 // of net::async_write, since we already instantiated it above for
526 // net::const_buffer.
527
528 yield net::async_write(stream_,
529 net::const_buffer(net::buffer(data_.message)), std::move(*this));
530 if(ec)
531 break;
532
533 // Set the timer and wait
534 data_.timer.expires_after(std::chrono::seconds(1));
535 yield data_.timer.async_wait(std::move(*this));
536 }
537 }
538
539 // The base class destroys the temporary data automatically,
540 // before invoking the final completion handler
541 this->complete_now(ec);
542 }
543
544 // Including this file undefines the macros for the coroutines
545 #include <boost/asio/unyield.hpp>
546 };
547
548 net::async_completion<WriteHandler, void(error_code)> completion(handler);
549 std::ostringstream os;
550 os << message;
551 op(stream, repeat_count, os.str(), completion.completion_handler);
552 return completion.result.get();
553 }
554
555 @endcode
556
557 @tparam Handler The type of the completion handler to store.
558 This type must meet the requirements of <em>CompletionHandler</em>.
559
560 @tparam Executor1 The type of the executor used when the handler has no
561 associated executor. An instance of this type must be provided upon
562 construction. The implementation will maintain an executor work guard
563 and a copy of this instance.
564
565 @tparam Allocator The allocator type to use if the handler does not
566 have an associated allocator. If this parameter is omitted, then
567 `std::allocator<void>` will be used. If the specified allocator is
568 not default constructible, an instance of the type must be provided
569 upon construction.
570
571 @see allocate_stable, async_base
572*/
573template<
574 class Handler,
575 class Executor1,
576 class Allocator = std::allocator<void>
577>
578class stable_async_base
579 : public async_base<
580 Handler, Executor1, Allocator>
581{
582 detail::stable_base* list_ = nullptr;
583
584 void
585 before_invoke_hook() override
586 {
587 detail::stable_base::destroy_list(list_);
588 }
589
590public:
591 /** Constructor

594 The type of this object must meet the requirements of <em>CompletionHandler</em>.
595 The implementation takes ownership of the handler by performing a decay-copy.
596
597 @param ex1 The executor associated with the implied I/O object

661 /** Allocate a temporary object to hold operation state.
662
663 The object will be destroyed just before the completion

666 template<
667 class State,

677 Args&&... args);

28/// An object of type @c executor_work_guard controls ownership of executor work
29/// within a scope.
30template <typename Executor>
31class executor_work_guard
32{
33public:
34 /// The underlying executor type.
35 typedef Executor executor_type;
36
37 /// Constructs a @c executor_work_guard object for the specified executor.
38 /**
39 * Stores a copy of @c e and calls <tt>on_work_started()</tt> on it.
40 */
41 explicit executor_work_guard(const executor_type& e) BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
42 : executor_(e),
43 owns_(true)
44 {
45 executor_.on_work_started();
36
←
Calling 'executor::on_work_started'
→
43
←
Returning from 'executor::on_work_started'
→
46 }
47
48 /// Copy constructor.
49 executor_work_guard(const executor_work_guard& other) BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
50 : executor_(other.executor_),
51 owns_(other.owns_)
52 {
53 if (owns_)
54 executor_.on_work_started();
55 }
56
57#if defined(BOOST_ASIO_HAS_MOVE1) || defined(GENERATING_DOCUMENTATION)
58 /// Move constructor.
59 executor_work_guard(executor_work_guard&& other) BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
60 : executor_(BOOST_ASIO_MOVE_CAST(Executor)static_cast<Executor&&>(other.executor_)),
61 owns_(other.owns_)
62 {
63 other.owns_ = false;
64 }
65#endif // defined(BOOST_ASIO_HAS_MOVE) || defined(GENERATING_DOCUMENTATION)
66
67 /// Destructor.
68 /**
69 * Unless the object has already been reset, or is in a moved-from state,
70 * calls <tt>on_work_finished()</tt> on the stored executor.
71 */
72 ~executor_work_guard()
73 {
74 if (owns_)
75 executor_.on_work_finished();
76 }
77
78 /// Obtain the associated executor.
79 executor_type get_executor() const BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
80 {
81 return executor_;
82 }
83
84 /// Whether the executor_work_guard object owns some outstanding work.
85 bool owns_work() const BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
86 {
87 return owns_;
88 }
89
90 /// Indicate that the work is no longer outstanding.
91 /*
92 * Unless the object has already been reset, or is in a moved-from state,
93 * calls <tt>on_work_finished()</tt> on the stored executor.
94 */
95 void reset() BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
96 {
97 if (owns_)
98 {
99 executor_.on_work_finished();
100 owns_ = false;
101 }
102 }
103
104private:
105 // Disallow assignment.
106 executor_work_guard& operator=(const executor_work_guard&);
107
108 executor_type executor_;
109 bool owns_;
110};

112/// Create an @ref executor_work_guard object.
113template <typename Executor>
114inline executor_work_guard<Executor> make_work_guard(const Executor& ex,
115 typename enable_if<is_executor<Executor>::value>::type* = 0)
116{
117 return executor_work_guard<Executor>(ex);
118}
119
120/// Create an @ref executor_work_guard object.
121template <typename ExecutionContext>
122inline executor_work_guard<typename ExecutionContext::executor_type>
123make_work_guard(ExecutionContext& ctx,
124 typename enable_if<
125 is_convertible<ExecutionContext&, execution_context&>::value>::type* = 0)
126{
127 return executor_work_guard<typename ExecutionContext::executor_type>(
128 ctx.get_executor());
129}

134make_work_guard(const T& t,
135 typename enable_if<!is_executor<T>::value &&
136 !is_convertible<T&, execution_context&>::value>::type* = 0)
137{
138 return executor_work_guard<typename associated_executor<T>::type>(
139 associated_executor<T>::get(t));
140}
141
142/// Create an @ref executor_work_guard object.
143template <typename T, typename Executor>
144inline executor_work_guard<typename associated_executor<T, Executor>::type>
145make_work_guard(const T& t, const Executor& ex,
146 typename enable_if<is_executor<Executor>::value>::type* = 0)
147{
148 return executor_work_guard<typename associated_executor<T, Executor>::type>(
149 associated_executor<T, Executor>::get(t, ex));
150}
151
152/// Create an @ref executor_work_guard object.
153template <typename T, typename ExecutionContext>
154inline executor_work_guard<typename associated_executor<T,
155 typename ExecutionContext::executor_type>::type>
156make_work_guard(const T& t, ExecutionContext& ctx,
157 typename enable_if<!is_executor<T>::value &&
158 !is_convertible<T&, execution_context&>::value &&
159 is_convertible<ExecutionContext&, execution_context&>::value>::type* = 0)
160{
161 return executor_work_guard<typename associated_executor<T,
162 typename ExecutionContext::executor_type>::type>(
163 associated_executor<T, typename ExecutionContext::executor_type>::get(

103 other.impl_ = 0;

112 impl_ = 0;
113 return *this;

146 /// Request the executor to invoke the given function object.
147 /**
148 * This function is used to ask the executor to execute the given function
149 * object. The function object is executed according to the rules of the
150 * target executor object.
151 *
152 * @param f The function object to be called. The executor will make a copy
153 * of the handler object as required. The function signature of the function
154 * object must be: @code void function(); @endcode
155 *
156 * @param a An allocator that may be used by the executor to allocate the
157 * internal storage needed for function invocation.
158 */
159 template <typename Function, typename Allocator>
160 void dispatch(BOOST_ASIO_MOVE_ARG(Function)Function&& f, const Allocator& a) const;

237 /// Compare two executors for equality.
238 friend bool operator==(const executor& a,
239 const executor& b) BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
240 {
241 if (a.impl_ == b.impl_)
242 return true;
243 if (!a.impl_ || !b.impl_)
244 return false;
245 return a.impl_->equals(b.impl_);
246 }
247
248 /// Compare two executors for inequality.
249 friend bool operator!=(const executor& a,
250 const executor& b) BOOST_ASIO_NOEXCEPTnoexcept
251 {
252 return !(a == b);
253 }
